        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Smlogg</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> "I'm curious to know how something supposedly random is stated as being biased and so deemed a challenge."</P><P>Simple, you cant code something in a computer to be totally random. Nothing in life is totally random. In order for something to be random in any electric software, a code must be inserted that will create a new number each time. Some of these codes are very good, some arent so good. This could be the latter situation. Just take /ran 100 for example. There are ways you can cheat the system. While its not possible to guess every number that will show up, you can guess based on past rolls what the number will be, in terms of a high, low, or mid roll. IE: roll ten low rolls in a row, the odds are, in eq at least, the the next roll will be 90 or above. In fact i will rig my rolls that way. ill roll multiple lows in a row, then when im grouped, i know my odds at a higher roll are better.</P><P>If you want proof of this, or just want to see somehting freaky, buy 2 ti 8x's of the same model, and then turn them both on and do a random of 1-10. Itll be the same number, each time you do it, until one calculator has used ran 1-10 at least one more time than the other.</P><P>Thus, nothing is completely random, and those spells that are hard to get just happened to be on the bad side of the randomization odds.</P><P><BR> </font></td>
