        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>argothdrinal</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> This is in regard to the spell biases measured by Scott. I don't know exactly how it is programmed, but one simple (and erroneous) approach to programming that would create bias is shown below: </P><P>Suppose mob_01 always drops 1 or no items. It is supposed to drop cleric_spell_01 20% of the time, druid_spell_01, 20% of the time, enchanter_spell_01 20% of the time and shaman_spell_01 20% of the time, and nothing 20% of the time. </P><P>The proper way to program this is to first determine the number of drops using a single /random 1 100. Then for each item dropped another single roll of /random 1 100 (1-25 is cleric spell, 26-50 is druid spell, 51-75 is enchanter spell, and 76-100 is shammy spell) determines what drops. </P><P>An easy error to make is to make sequential 25% rolls (or even worse, 20% rolls -- this is a standard freshman/sophomore error in an algorithms class). First roll for a cleric spell [the order is arbitrary, I have assumed alphabetical order... the point is the same... whoever is at the bottom of the table is screwed] (1-25 cleric spell drops, 26-100 it doesn't). If a spell has dropped, stop rolling. Next roll for a druid spell (1-25 druid spell drops, 26-100 it doesn't). Stop if spell drops. Next roll for enchanter spell (1-25 enchanter spell drops, 26-100 it doesn't). Stop if spell drops. Finally, if no other spells have dropped, roll for the shaman spell (1-25 shaman spell drops, 26-100 it doesn't). If no spell, then corpse is MT. Using this approach, the probability of a shaman spell dropping is not nearly 25%. It is actually (0.75^3)*0.25 = 10.5%. </P><P>(For those interested: assuming this error has been made, the cleric spell drops 25% of the time, the druid spell drops 18.75% of the time, the enchanter spell drops 14.1% of the time and nothing drops about 32% of the time. Quite a far cry from the intended distribution. In general the longer the list and the lower the probability of a single event, the more biased the distribution.). </P><P>The erroneous approach is consistent with both the rarity of certain spells and with Scott's observations. </P><P>Argoth, Shaman of Drinal <BR>Divine Intervention</P><P></P><P></P><P>Edited by - argothdrinal on 02/21/2002  13:35:59</font></td>
